    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a high-ceiling outlook, anchored by **Yordan Alvarez (75.76)** and **Junior Caminero (73.35)**. Alvarez is our definitive primary play; despite a traditional platoon disadvantage against southpaw Kyle Freeland, his elite xwOBA (.393) and a significant +14% park factor boost make him a must-start. Caminero similarly benefits from a favorable matchup against Javier Assad (4.83 xERA), with his elevated spot in the order providing the necessary volume to capitalize on the weak opposing starter. Meanwhile, **Trea Turner (70.39)** and **Kyle Schwarber (69.61)** serve as the engine of today\u2019s offense; both see their stocks rise against Robbie Ray, as the predicted wind blowing out (+5%) leverages their power profiles, making them the most reliable anchors for a 5x5 Roto push.\n\nNavigating the fringes of the lineup remains a tactical necessity given our scarcity-first approach to stolen bases. **Pete Crow-Armstrong (58.81)** was prioritized over bench options like **Caleb Durbin (46.02)** primarily due to a substantial +14% dynamic platoon advantage against Drew Rasmussen. While Durbin remains a high-upside asset, his proximity to the bottom of the order and a negative wind-in penalty dropped him below the optimizer\u2019s floor for active service. Conversely, we are keeping a close watch on **Christian Yelich (42.06)**; his score is suppressed significantly by Garrett Crochet\u2019s elite skill profile (2.86 xERA) and an unfavorable wind-in factor. He remains in the starting lineup to balance the roster, but he carries the highest risk of an early-game sub if the early innings against Crochet prove unproductive. \n\nAll projections today remain contingent on official lineup confirmation. While we have built our model assuming historical batting orders, any shifts in lineup hierarchy\u2014particularly for **Dillon Dingler** or **Hyeseong Kim**\u2014could swing their efficiency scores into the sub-40 danger zone. We are proceeding with an aggressive stance in the outfield to maximize our speed potential, but managers should monitor weather alerts at any parks reporting gusty wind-in conditions, as these will disproportionately penalize our power-reliant starters.",
